<abstract>
	<para>
		<application>gtranslator</application> is a comfortable editor
		for the gettext po files which are mostly the basis for i18n
		in GNOME and other desktop environments.
	</para>
</abstract>

</artheader>

<sect1 id="introduction">
	<title>Introduction</title>
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> offers you many 
			comfortable dialogs to edit the po files fields and to navigate comfortably
			through the messages of the po file.
		</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="features">
	<title>Major features of <application>gtranslator</application></title>
		<para>
			gtranslator has got many features which are 
			<emphasis>useful</emphasis>
			for editing the gettext po files. The major features are:
			<itemizedlist>
				<listitem>
					<para>Crashless and quick editing of
					gettext po files</para>
				</listitem>	
				<listitem>
					<para>Very low memory usage</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Navigation inside the fuzzy,
					untranslated and translated
					messages</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Regular expressions based
					find/search function</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Compile function for testing
					your po files</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Status indication with detailed
					information at the statusbar and a
					<emphasis>useful and correct</emphasis>
					progress bar</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Advanced history list with
					<emphasis>
						project name and version
					</emphasis>
					instead of only showing
					the filename</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Opening of gzip&apos;ed and compiled
					(.mo/.gmo) gettext po files</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Opening of remote po files via
					GnomeVFS (and http, ftp, nfs and other
					access routines of GnomeVFS).</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Editing with the help of a
					"special char" instead of only hardly
					recognizable free spaces</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Update function to update the po
					file with the (if installed)
					xml-i18n-tools</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Query capability to get already made
					translations from other gettext domains</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Colorschemes for changing the syntax colors
					on the fly -- these colorschemes are xml files and
					easy to change/adept.</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Autogeneration and filling up of the default
					header if a new, fresh pot file is taken into
					gtranslator</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>A simple Nautilus view with which you can
					see the header fields of a po file</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Find, replace dialogs and functionality</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>Obsolete entries in the po file are kept now
					at preference of the user (if you want them you get
					them in your po files)</para>
				</listitem>
			</itemizedlist>
		</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="commandlinearguments">
	<title>Command line arguments</title>
		<para>
			<application>gtranslator</application> understands some
			command line arguments:
			<itemizedlist>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--help</emphasis> Shows you a
					litte help message on the command line.
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--version</emphasis> Tells you
					the version of <application>gtranslator
					</application> you&apos;re using.
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--display</emphasis> Let&apos;s you
					define the display to start 
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					on.
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--webalize</emphasis> Prints
					out a htmlized output file (you must
					give the html output filename as the
					next argument) of the po file.
					</para>
					<para>
					An example call would be:
					<emphasis>
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					--webalize=Evolution.html tr.po
					</emphasis>
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--scheme</emphasis> Sets the
					syntax color scheme to the given file
					</para>
					<para>
					For example:
					<emphasis>
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					--scheme=Schemefile
					</emphasis>
					</para>
				</listitem>
				<listitem>
					<para>
					<emphasis>--geometry</emphasis> Let&apos;s
					you define a standard geometry string
					to which the gtranslator window will
					conform.
					</para>
					<para>
					An example call would be:
					<emphasis>
					<application>gtranslator</application>
					--geometry="320x240+0+0" tr.po
					</emphasis>
					(This opens gtranslator at "+0+0", the
					left upper corner, with a size of 
					320x240).
					</para>
				</listitem>	
			</itemizedlist>	
		</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="aa">
	<title>Autoaccomplishment</title>
		<sect2 id="idea">
			<title>Idea</title>
			<para>
			Autoaccomplishment means the completion of non-translated
			strings with already made and installed translations from the
			user-defined default query domain (which is a program like
			"<application>nautilus</application>").
			</para>
		</sect2>
		<sect2 id="praxis">
			<title>Practical use</title>
			<para>
			To use the autoaccomplish feature of gtranslator you&apos;ve got to
			setup two main things in your personal preference.
				<itemizedlist>
					<listitem>
						<para>Your language details in the <emphasis>
						Language settings</emphasis> page of the
						preferences dialog.
						</para>
					</listitem>
					<listitem>
						<para>Once you&apos;ve set up your language the available
						query domains will be parsed on the next startup of
						<application>gtranslator</application>. Then you can
						select your default query domain in the <emphasis>
						Personal informations</emphasis> page of the preferences
						dialog.
						</para>
					</listitem>
				</itemizedlist>
			After you&apos;ve done this setup steps you can simply use the autoaccomplishment
			feature by selection the corresponding menu option in the <emphasis>
			_File</emphasis> menu.
			</para>
			<para>
			All non-translated messages will be checked if they&apos;ve
			been already translated for the default query domain and if everything went right
			the translation found in the default query domain will be simply used as the
			translation for the corresponding msgid.
			</para>
		</sect2>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="colorschemes">
	<title>Color schemes</title>
		<para>
			Color schemes define the colors of the different syntax elements in gtranslator.
		</para>
		<para>
			The file format for color schemes is quite easy and based on <emphasis>XML</emphasis>.
			The default colors are included as the <emphasis>default.xml</emphasis> color scheme and
			can be consulted if you want to write an own color scheme.
		</para>
		<para>
			The tags are <emphasis>all</emphasis> mandatory and the &lt;author&gt; tag has to be before 
			all &lt;color&gt; tags in the file. The available color targets can be also obtained from the 
			default.xml file.
		</para>
		<para>
			Many color schemes are already distributed with the default package of gtranslator and can be
			easily selected/changed from the preferences dialog on the "Fonts, colors and color schemes"
			page.
		</para>
</sect1>

